Currently, high gas fees limit the capabilities of smart contracts. 

TON smart contracts can reach their ultimate potential of replacing the need for intermediaries due to the infinite scalability of the network. (5/5)

Most contracts reside in just one shard, which is enough to host their operations. 

However, more complex, high-load smart contracts can have an instance of their program stored in each shardchain for a large commission. (4/5)
The TON Virtual Machine handles the deployment of smart contracts on the TON Network. It uses tagged data types that give it the capability to handle complex operations. (3/5)

Once the smart contract, or series of contracts, has been executed, the blockchain is updated with its record. 

This means that the output of the contract cannot be changed, and its record is available to view by the parties who have been granted permission. (2/5)

Smart contracts are “if/when…then…” statements that are written into code in order to execute commands when the specified parameters are met. 

They act as a way to automate agreements without an intermediary having to approve them. (1/5)
